[
    {
        "content": "<p>What do you think about a file <code>ring_theory.polynomial.eisenstein</code> about Eiseinstein polynomials? Something like</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">ring_theory.eisenstein_criterion</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">universe</span> <span class=\"n\">u</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">R</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">comm_semiring</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">namespace</span> <span class=\"n\">polynomial</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">structure</span> <span class=\"n\">is_eisenstein_at</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">ùìü</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">ideal</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">polynomial</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">monic</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">f.monic</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">mem</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àÄ</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span> <span class=\"n\">f.nat_degree</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚Üí</span> <span class=\"n\">f.coeff</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àà</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùìü</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">not_mem</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">f.coeff</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àâ</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùìü</span> <span class=\"bp\">^</span> <span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">end</span> <span class=\"n\">polynomial</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Currently we have irreducibility via <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/polynomial.irreducible_of_eisenstein_criterion\">docs#polynomial.irreducible_of_eisenstein_criterion</a>, but I plan to add more results concerning Eisenstein polynomials in <code>flt-regular</code>, especially the fact that if the minimal polynomial of an algebraic integer <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> is Eisenstein at <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span> then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}[x]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>-maximal inside <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">O</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{O}_{\\mathbb{Q}(x)}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0385em;vertical-align:-0.3552em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198em;margin-left:-0.0278em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">Q</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">‚Äã</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3552em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 268740325,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642704890
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You'd likely want to make the ideal over which it is Eisenstein explicit</p>",
        "id": 268740830,
        "sender_full_name": "Yakov Pechersky",
        "timestamp": 1642705131
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, of course</p>",
        "id": 268741186,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705259
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, why do you want the polynomial to be monic and not simply have leading coefficient not in the ideal?</p>",
        "id": 268741923,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642705568
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was expecting that objection <span aria-label=\"grinning\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f600\" role=\"img\" title=\"grinning\">:grinning:</span></p>",
        "id": 268742009,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705614
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually you could change the for all condition to simply skip the natdegree and quantify over all nats</p>",
        "id": 268742046,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642705637
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, of course it depends on the application we have in mind. For irreducibility primitive is enough, but for what I want to do I think I need monic</p>",
        "id": 268742068,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705646
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course I can just state my result for a monic Eisenstein polynomial</p>",
        "id": 268742093,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705664
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the more general context of Newton polygons, it makes sense to think about just having valuation zero, but I am not planning to use this soon, so I am happy with whatever, really!</p>",
        "id": 268742277,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642705739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the point is to try to guess how many times this def will be used. If 90% of the time is with <code>monic</code> is probably a good idea to have it in the  definition</p>",
        "id": 268742284,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705744
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I need stuff like</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">lemma</span> <span class=\"n\">eisenstein</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">P</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">polynomial</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hP</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">eval</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"n\">P</span> <span class=\"bp\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">p</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">}</span>\n  <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hmo</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">P.monic</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hdiv</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àÄ</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span> <span class=\"n\">P.nat_degree</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">p</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚à£</span> <span class=\"n\">P.coeff</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">‚àÄ</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">P.nat_degree</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚â§</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚Üí</span> <span class=\"n\">p</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚à£</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"bp\">^</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 268742384,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I want to write <code>x ^ i</code> as a linear combination of lower powers</p>",
        "id": 268742457,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705821
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(well, here eisenstein is not necessary, but it is later)</p>",
        "id": 268742526,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642705856
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My inclination would still be to make <code>mem</code> an iff with n ‚â† natdegree</p>",
        "id": 268743223,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642706178
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't see the point. The definition will be a little more elegant, but to check it holds one need more work. Of course this can be a lemma.</p>",
        "id": 268744332,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642706695
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Regardless of the issue of what definition you use, I <em>think</em> that if you switch the order of the ideal and the polynomial in the definition, dot-notation allows for</p>\n<p>Àãf.is_eisentein_at PÀã</p>",
        "id": 268750227,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642709379
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, my main motivation for wanting not necessarily monic polynomials has its roots in this proof of the irreducibility of the truncated exponential polynomials:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://mattbaker.blog/2014/05/02/newton-polygons-and-galois-groups/#more-612\">https://mattbaker.blog/2014/05/02/newton-polygons-and-galois-groups/#more-612</a></p>\n<p>However, it may be better to start from somewhere and then incrementally generalize.</p>",
        "id": 268751503,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642709968
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Mmh, wikipedia agrees with your definition...</p>",
        "id": 268752459,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642710476
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So let's drop monic</p>",
        "id": 268752507,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642710484
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Honestly, for me \"Eisenstein\" either means \"prove the p'th cyclotomic polynomial is irreducible\" or is a special case of Newton polygons.  All these questions of generalizations are mostly academic... <span aria-label=\"shrug\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f937\" role=\"img\" title=\"shrug\">:shrug:</span></p>",
        "id": 268753334,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1642710825
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The criterion I am proving is really useful in real life. The first example is of course cyclotomic fields, but any time one is able to compute the discriminant of a number field it is a good try to compute the ring of integers.</p>",
        "id": 268756469,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1642712267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/11577\">#11577</a> I've PRed some technical  lemmas, like</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">lemma</span> <span class=\"n\">pow_nat_degree_le_of_aeval_zero_of_eisenstein_criterion_mem_map</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">algebra</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">}</span>\n  <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">f</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">polynomial</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hx</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">aeval</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"n\">f</span> <span class=\"bp\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hmo</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">f.monic</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n  <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hdiv</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àÄ</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span> <span class=\"n\">f.nat_degree</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">f.coeff</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àà</span> <span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span>\n  <span class=\"bp\">‚àÄ</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f.map</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">algebra_map</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">nat_degree</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚â§</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚Üí</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"bp\">^</span> <span class=\"n\">i</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚àà</span> <span class=\"n\">p.map</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">algebra_map</span> <span class=\"n\">R</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I will use these for Eisenstein polynomials, but the real hypothesis is weaker than being Eiseinstein, so I put them in the most basic file I found.</p>\n<p>Would it be reasonable to have them in the file about Eiseinstein polynomials? (In this case we can have them as stated, or directly for Eiseinstein polynomials. Or maybe we can have something like <code>is_weak_eisenstein_at</code>.) Note that this file will import a lot of stuff, since the interesting results about Eisenstein polynomials require quite a big machinery to be proved.</p>",
        "id": 269157128,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1643052358
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>After some thinking I am now convinced it's  OK to have these results in the <code>eiseinstein.lean</code> file, even if importing it it's not very convenient. The reason is that these results are really technical, and probably nobody will ever use them.</p>",
        "id": 269436548,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1643213386
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry, I missed your previous message. I think it's fine that a file on Eisenstein polynomials has heavy imports. If it becomes a problem, we can restructure later.</p>",
        "id": 269436855,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1643213487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No problem :)</p>",
        "id": 269436883,
